{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"36326b39-cc34-42ce-ac48-571d415aa132","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class span support**: `T[]` now has an implicit conversion to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` that participates in **overload resolution**. This causes `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)   // ← new winner\n```\n\ninstead of the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)           // ← .NET 9 winner\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be represented in expression trees. The interpreted expression-tree executor (`preferInterpretation: true`) fails at runtime when it encounters this call.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload. Any of these work:\n\n**Option A — cast to `IEnumerable<int>`** (minimal change):\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly**:\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option C — use `AsEnumerable()`**:\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);\n```\n\nAll three force resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`, which expression trees can represent. The fix applies whether you use `preferInterpretation: true` or JIT-compiled delegates.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6c974745-fb08-43df-9dc2-ba09f76c898f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `expr.Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related